00:39:56,093 --> 00:39:58,229
-Stop for a minute.
-Leave Me Natto-lone!

949
00:39:58,295 --> 00:40:01,665
Please!

950
00:40:02,967 --> 00:40:04,535
-Leave Me Natto-lone!
-Leave Me Natto-lone!

951
00:40:04,602 --> 00:40:06,670
-You can't do this.
-Ring the bell already.

952
00:40:06,737 --> 00:40:08,939
-I'm done.
-You are?

953
00:40:09,006 --> 00:40:10,241
You've become much faster too.

954
00:40:10,307 --> 00:40:12,076
Are you done?

955
00:40:12,143 --> 00:40:14,712
CHOI KANG-ROK FINISHES
LEAVE ME NATTO-LONE!

956
00:40:14,779 --> 00:40:16,046
It looks so good.

957
00:40:16,113 --> 00:40:20,684
-Great job. You've come a long way.
-Thank you.

958
00:40:20,751 --> 00:40:24,789
Sung-tae's order was named
Fridge Game: At this rate, it'll all rot!

959
00:40:24,855 --> 00:40:28,125
And the dishes are both complete.

960
00:40:28,192 --> 00:40:29,560
Oh!

961
00:40:29,627 --> 00:40:30,961
What's wrong?

962
00:40:31,028 --> 00:40:32,396
-It's this.
-You forgot to put it up.

963
00:40:32,463 --> 00:40:33,597
-The green onion?
-Yes.

964
00:40:33,664 --> 00:40:35,566
-You forgot.
-That's important.

965
00:40:35,633 --> 00:40:37,968
You must ask your opponent
for understanding.

966
00:40:38,035 --> 00:40:40,204
<i>You had time left,</i>

967
00:40:40,271 --> 00:40:43,741
<i>so let's ask your opponent</i>
<i>if she'll allow you to put it up.</i>

968
00:40:43,808 --> 00:40:45,109
Chef Sohyi?

969
00:40:45,176 --> 00:40:49,046
When chefs cook,
we put in the ingredients as we think.

970
00:40:49,113 --> 00:40:50,981
"Why do I have to put this in?"

971
00:40:51,048 --> 00:40:54,018
How will the taste change
with or without the green onion?

972
00:40:54,084 --> 00:40:56,554
What does it taste like
without green onion,

973
00:40:56,620 --> 00:40:58,489
and what's it like with green onion?

974
00:40:58,556 --> 00:40:59,557
I would say

975
00:40:59,623 --> 00:41:03,561
it'll taste like green onion
if I put it in, and it won't if I don't.

976
00:41:04,528 --> 00:41:06,630
-Yes, so…
-That's obvious.

977
00:41:08,232 --> 00:41:11,268
-Jeez, dear me.
-"Dear me."

978
00:41:11,335 --> 00:41:12,937
Will you let him put it in?

979
00:41:13,003 --> 00:41:15,039
-Just let him do it.
-Just let him do it?

980
00:41:15,105 --> 00:41:17,408
-She says yes, so go ahead.
-Okay.

981
00:41:17,475 --> 00:41:19,910
I'll top it for him when he tries it.

982
00:41:19,977 --> 00:41:22,780
Now, Chef Sohyi finished first.

983
00:41:23,414 --> 00:41:26,116
TTEOKGUK REINTERPRETED
IN KIM SOHYI'S STYLE

984
00:41:27,051 --> 00:41:32,423
MADE WITH RADISH, KIMCHI,
AND DOENJANG

985
00:41:33,624 --> 00:41:37,795
CHEF KIM SOHYI'S
MASTER TTEOKGUK KOREA

986
00:41:37,862 --> 00:41:40,231
-You said you loved <i>tteokguk</i>.
-Yes.

987
00:41:40,297 --> 00:41:42,466
Will it humor his palate?

988
00:41:42,533 --> 00:41:45,169
That's Master <i>Tteokguk</i> Korea.

989
00:41:45,703 --> 00:41:46,704
CURIOUS

990
00:41:46,770 --> 00:41:47,771
He took a big bite.

991
00:41:49,440 --> 00:41:50,441
Man.

992
00:41:50,508 --> 00:41:51,575
-Hmm?
-"Man."

993
00:41:51,642 --> 00:41:52,943
What's it like?

994
00:41:53,010 --> 00:41:57,982
It's a dish that cleverly uses
the scent of perilla oil.

995
00:41:58,048 --> 00:42:01,519
<i>-She stir-fried radish in it, I think.</i>
<i>-You're right.</i>

996
00:42:01,585 --> 00:42:04,755
<i>-I see.</i>
<i>-Radish and perilla oil go well together.</i>

997
00:42:04,822 --> 00:42:05,823
<i>-I see.</i>
<i>-I see.</i>

998
00:42:06,857 --> 00:42:09,593
And I'm curious
what role kimchi plays in that dish.

999
00:42:09,660 --> 00:42:12,663
-She put everything in there.
-She did.

1000
00:42:12,730 --> 00:42:13,931
My gosh.

1001
00:42:13,998 --> 00:42:16,267
CRUNCHY

1002
00:42:16,934 --> 00:42:21,772
The dish is more appetizing because
she didn't boil kimchi with other stuff.

1003
00:42:21,839 --> 00:42:23,874
I'm glad it's just the topping.

1004
00:42:23,941 --> 00:42:25,876
The kimchi must've tasted fresh.

1005
00:42:25,943 --> 00:42:29,046
It was rather crunchy too.

1006
00:42:29,113 --> 00:42:33,117
I thought it would've been too soggy
if she cooked it in the broth.

1007
00:42:33,183 --> 00:42:36,654
But the crunchiness of the topping
adds a nice touch.

1008
00:42:36,720 --> 00:42:38,622
The topping was cleverly used.

1009
00:42:38,689 --> 00:42:41,792
We usually eat <i>tteokguk </i>with beef topping
because of its light taste,

1010
00:42:41,859 --> 00:42:45,696
-but this one was more refreshing.
-It was more refreshing.

1011
00:42:45,763 --> 00:42:49,099
And I can sense
a bit of Gyeongsang style too.

1012
00:42:49,166 --> 00:42:51,035
-I see.
-I see.

1013
00:42:51,101 --> 00:42:53,637
That sounds great.
Next, Leave Me Natto-lone.

1014
00:42:55,072 --> 00:42:58,342
PASTA MADE WITH NATTO

1015
00:42:58,976 --> 00:43:03,581
LAVER, KIMCHI,
CHICKEN BREAST, AND NATTO

1016
00:43:04,214 --> 00:43:08,886
CHEF CHOI KANG-ROK'S
LEAVE ME NATTO-LONE

1017
00:43:09,820 --> 00:43:11,021
Green onion.

1018
00:43:11,088 --> 00:43:13,424
You need a little bit of this.

1019
00:43:13,490 --> 00:43:15,025
That must make a difference.

1020
00:43:15,092 --> 00:43:18,929
-Chef Kang-rok rarely does this.
-It's prettier too.

1021
00:43:19,964 --> 00:43:22,399
-Okay.
-Should I mix it in?

1022
00:43:22,466 --> 00:43:25,836
-Mix it in, and try it with lots of beans.
-Okay.

1023
00:43:25,903 --> 00:43:29,173
-You mentioned natto.
-And you like it too.

1024
00:43:29,239 --> 00:43:32,810
-I love the name. Leave Me Natto-lone.
-Yes.

1025
00:43:32,876 --> 00:43:35,346
It's odd how it smells like <i>cheonggukjang</i>.

1026
00:43:35,412 --> 00:43:36,947
It smells like <i>cheonggukjang</i>?

1027
00:43:37,615 --> 00:43:41,118
Sung-tae said he had natto every morning.

1028
00:43:42,286 --> 00:43:44,855
-That means he likes natto.
-Yes.

1029
00:43:44,922 --> 00:43:49,393
I really like this smell,
as well as the smell of <i>cheonggukjang</i>.

1030
00:43:49,460 --> 00:43:53,330
The smell became more amplified
when natto was heated.

1031
00:43:53,397 --> 00:43:57,301
-It tastes like a strong Korean dish.
-Is that so?

1032
00:43:57,368 --> 00:43:59,436
Many people eat natto for their health.

1033
00:44:00,137 --> 00:44:01,872
JUST AS THE CHEF WANTED,

1034
00:44:02,439 --> 00:44:06,310
HE SLURPS THE PASTA DOWN

1035
00:44:06,377 --> 00:44:08,379
He's eating a lot.

1036
00:44:08,445 --> 00:44:11,081
You asked him to use chicken breast,
and he did.

1037
00:44:11,148 --> 00:44:12,449
-How's that?
-Can you taste it?

1038
00:44:12,516 --> 00:44:14,685
Yes, I can. He put in quite a lot.

1039
00:44:14,752 --> 00:44:16,787
PROUD

1040
00:44:16,854 --> 00:44:18,889
-He put in a lot?
-He put in a lot.

1041
00:44:18,956 --> 00:44:21,058
-You wanted him to use it up.
-Yes.

1042
00:44:21,125 --> 00:44:25,362
<i>The chicken breast was</i>
<i>already seasoned with salt and pepper,</i>

1043
00:44:25,429 --> 00:44:28,065
<i>and it seems like</i>
<i>he brought it out on purpose.</i>

1044
00:44:28,132 --> 00:44:29,433
HAPPY WITH BOTH DISHES

1045
00:44:29,500 --> 00:44:30,868
He didn't season it too much.

1046
00:44:30,934 --> 00:44:32,703
He let the taste
of the ingredients come through.

1047
00:44:32,770 --> 00:44:34,571
-Let's have a taste too.
-Okay.

1048
00:44:34,638 --> 00:44:38,308
First, let's try Master <i>Tteokguk</i> Korea.

1049
00:44:38,375 --> 00:44:39,643
And j-hope.

1050
00:44:40,477 --> 00:44:41,779
It looks so good.

1051
00:44:43,247 --> 00:44:45,082
This is so interesting.

1052
00:44:45,949 --> 00:44:49,019
The perilla leaf has a presence.

1053
00:44:49,086 --> 00:44:50,454
It's so intriguing.

1054
00:44:50,521 --> 00:44:52,089
When we eat <i>tteokguk</i>,

1055
00:44:52,156 --> 00:44:54,792
we take a bite of that,
then eat the side dishes too.

1056
00:44:54,858 --> 00:44:56,994
We'll have a bite of <i>tteokguk</i>,

1057
00:44:57,061 --> 00:44:59,196
then seasoned radish,
perilla leaf, or kimchi.

1058
00:44:59,263 --> 00:45:02,900
And the flavor keeps changing like that
while eating this single bowl.

1059
00:45:02,966 --> 00:45:05,903
Chef Sohyi must've missed
such side dishes.

1060
00:45:05,969 --> 00:45:07,304
Not only are you handsome,

1061
00:45:07,371 --> 00:45:10,441
-but you're eloquent too.
-He's right.

1062
00:45:10,507 --> 00:45:15,245
As she cooked, she said
she'd put in whatever she wanted to eat.

1063
00:45:15,312 --> 00:45:18,982
These were the flavors she missed
while she lived in Vienna.

1064
00:45:19,049 --> 00:45:21,585
That's kind of moving too.

1065
00:45:21,652 --> 00:45:23,387
And everything's nicely balanced too.

1066
00:45:23,454 --> 00:45:27,558
When a dish is made with many ingredients,
one of them is bound to stand out.

1067
00:45:27,624 --> 00:45:32,396
In this mix,
perilla oil had the biggest presence.

1068
00:45:32,463 --> 00:45:35,966
-j-hope is scratching the bowl.
-He's scratching the bottom.

1069
00:45:36,033 --> 00:45:40,204
-I need some more.
-I see.

1070
00:45:40,270 --> 00:45:43,407
I liked how the soup was
very clean and light.

1071
00:45:43,474 --> 00:45:48,245
<i>In contrast, the toppings were</i>
<i>seasoned perfectly.</i>

1072
00:45:48,312 --> 00:45:51,849
<i>-It had a great balance as a bowl.</i>
<i>-I see.</i>

1073
00:45:51,915 --> 00:45:55,052
This time, let's try Leave Me Natto-lone.

1074
00:45:57,521 --> 00:45:58,522
SLURP

1075
00:45:59,957 --> 00:46:00,958
SHOOP

1076
00:46:05,963 --> 00:46:11,502
People who like natto
will be obsessed with this dish.

1077
00:46:11,568 --> 00:46:15,973
It tastes very healthy and well-balanced.

1078
00:46:16,039 --> 00:46:18,108
-It's good.
-It's so good.

1079
00:46:19,009 --> 00:46:20,477
AND JUST LIKE THE LAST ONE,

1080
00:46:20,544 --> 00:46:25,149
HE'S EMPTYING OUT THIS ONE TOO

1081
00:46:28,185 --> 00:46:29,953
MOVED

1082
00:46:30,020 --> 00:46:32,055
j-hope just emptied out his bowl again.

1083
00:46:32,122 --> 00:46:33,957
CLEAN

1084
00:46:34,024 --> 00:46:36,293
-I already had a lot…
-Yes.

1085
00:46:36,360 --> 00:46:37,361
…but I can't stop.

1086
00:46:37,427 --> 00:46:39,530
-You can't stop eating.
-That's what's odd.

1087
00:46:39,596 --> 00:46:42,366
Both dishes have the flavor of a dish

1088
00:46:42,432 --> 00:46:45,035
that makes you crave it more and more.

1089
00:46:45,102 --> 00:46:47,671
-You can keep eating this.
-I want to keep tasting this.

1090
00:46:47,738 --> 00:46:49,239
The green onion adds good balance.

1091
00:46:49,306 --> 00:46:50,941
-Yes.
-It balances out the greasiness.

1092
00:46:51,008 --> 00:46:53,911
<i>-It becomes a good kick.</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

1093
00:46:53,977 --> 00:46:55,779
It has that refreshing touch.

1094
00:46:55,846 --> 00:46:59,082
It doesn't feel too much
even as you're eating pasta.

1095
00:46:59,149 --> 00:47:01,451
It's time for Sung-tae to decide.

1096
00:47:01,518 --> 00:47:04,655
Many viewers are curious
to see what decision he makes.

1097
00:47:04,721 --> 00:47:07,457
Press one for Choi Kang-rok,

1098
00:47:07,524 --> 00:47:09,860
and press two for Kim Sohyi.

1099
00:47:09,927 --> 00:47:11,795
Please make your decision.

1100
00:47:11,862 --> 00:47:15,666
-He sighs first.
-It must be hard.

1101
00:47:15,732 --> 00:47:18,068
-Please make your decision and press…
-Press…

1102
00:47:18,135 --> 00:47:20,137
-…the button!
-…the button!

1103
00:47:22,139 --> 00:47:23,640
-I pressed it.
-He did.

1104
00:47:23,707 --> 00:47:27,377
-He pressed it.
-He pressed it quietly.

1105
00:47:27,444 --> 00:47:28,912
Gosh.

1106
00:47:28,979 --> 00:47:32,115
-Let's find out Sung-tae's choice!
-Let's find out!

1107
00:47:32,182 --> 00:47:33,183
Who could it be?

1108
00:47:33,250 --> 00:47:37,254
-Fridge Game: At this rate, it'll all rot!
-At this rate, it'll all rot!

1109
00:47:37,321 --> 00:47:39,456
-Who'll win?
-Did he choose

1110
00:47:39,523 --> 00:47:41,692
-Chef Sohyi?
-Did he?

1111
00:47:41,758 --> 00:47:44,094
Or is it Chef Kang-rok?

1112
00:47:44,161 --> 00:47:45,429
Is it <i>tteokguk</i>

1113
00:47:45,495 --> 00:47:47,197
or natto?

1114
00:47:47,264 --> 00:47:49,700
-Who did Sung-tae choose?
-Leave Me Natto-lone!

1115
00:47:49,766 --> 00:47:52,536
-Who was it?
-Master <i>Tteokguk</i> Korea!

1116
00:47:52,603 --> 00:47:53,937
Show us!

1117
00:47:54,004 --> 00:47:55,372
KIM SOHYI WINS

1118
00:47:55,439 --> 00:47:56,440
Show us!

1119
00:47:56,506 --> 00:47:59,042
CHEF KIM SOHYI'S
MASTER TTEOKGUK KOREA WINS

1120
00:47:59,109 --> 00:48:01,078
<i>Tteokguk</i> wins!

1121
00:48:01,144 --> 00:48:02,713
THE WINNER IS KIM SOHYI

1122
00:48:03,280 --> 00:48:05,449
-It was Chef Sohyi.
-He can't stand a chance.

1123
00:48:07,317 --> 00:48:09,920
-You did well.
-It must've been hard.

1124
00:48:09,987 --> 00:48:12,122
-Yours was really good.
-Thank you.

1125
00:48:12,189 --> 00:48:15,025
-<i>Tteokguk</i>.
-I'm sweating.

1126
00:48:15,092 --> 00:48:19,263
This is a tough place to stand in.

1127
00:48:19,329 --> 00:48:20,831
It's her first time getting evaluated.

1128
00:48:20,898 --> 00:48:22,766
-It is.
-It was her first time.

1129
00:48:22,833 --> 00:48:26,136
j-hope, which one would you have chosen?

1130
00:48:26,803 --> 00:48:27,804
GOSH

1131
00:48:28,572 --> 00:48:30,374
Why are you asking me this?

1132
00:48:30,440 --> 00:48:32,376
Gosh, it's so hard.

1133
00:48:32,976 --> 00:48:33,977
I would've chosen…

1134
00:48:35,779 --> 00:48:40,217
-I would've chosen the natto.
-Leave Me Natto-lone.

1135
00:48:40,284 --> 00:48:43,987
First off, I like noodles and pasta.

1136
00:48:44,054 --> 00:48:45,522
Leave Me Natto-lone.

1137
00:48:46,857 --> 00:48:49,359
The result is already out.
He can't win anyway.

1138
00:48:49,426 --> 00:48:50,994
Did you prefer the natto?

1139
00:48:51,061 --> 00:48:54,131
Yes, I like dishes like <i>mazesoba</i>,

1140
00:48:54,197 --> 00:48:58,969
and it was much smoother to eat.

1141
00:48:59,036 --> 00:49:01,138
-It just depended on our preferences.
-Yes.

1142
00:49:01,204 --> 00:49:05,042
-He prefers pasta, and I prefer <i>tteokguk</i>.
-I see.

1143
00:49:05,108 --> 00:49:08,145
Was Kang-rok still the same guy
as the one you saw 12 years ago?

1144
00:49:08,211 --> 00:49:09,880
Yes, he's the same but improved.

1145
00:49:09,947 --> 00:49:13,951
He only cooked Japanese food then,
but he could now add pasta

1146
00:49:14,017 --> 00:49:16,887
and change his recipe around,
which is very tough to do.

1147
00:49:16,954 --> 00:49:18,789
He's upped his game.

1148
00:49:18,855 --> 00:49:20,223
Thank you.

1149
00:49:21,658 --> 00:49:26,296
I used to be evaluated by her,

1150
00:49:26,363 --> 00:49:31,468
so it was an honor that she was willing
to compete with me like this.

1151
00:49:31,535 --> 00:49:33,837
-In the middle of the match…
-Yes.

1152
00:49:33,904 --> 00:49:37,407
<i>…she called Chef Hyun-suk</i>
<i>to help Chef Kang-rok out.</i>

1153
00:49:37,474 --> 00:49:39,276
<i>That was when we realized</i>

1154
00:49:39,343 --> 00:49:43,580
<i>how much she cares for Chef Kang-rok.</i>

1155
00:49:43,647 --> 00:49:47,484
All parents think their children are
still young and fragile.

1156
00:49:47,551 --> 00:49:48,552
You're right.

1157
00:49:48,618 --> 00:49:50,887
I knew he'd do well,
but I was just worried.

1158
00:49:50,954 --> 00:49:52,723
That's why I wanted him to help.

1159
00:49:52,789 --> 00:49:54,024
He would've done fine without him.

1160
00:49:54,091 --> 00:49:56,126
-You're right.
-That was a touching moment.

1161
00:49:56,193 --> 00:50:00,931
Sung-tae will put a star
on Chef Sohyi's chest.

1162
00:50:00,998 --> 00:50:02,265
Please come on out.

1163
00:50:02,332 --> 00:50:03,900
Thank you.

1164
00:50:03,967 --> 00:50:06,370
-Thank you.
-You won a star,

1165
00:50:06,436 --> 00:50:08,338
thanks to Sung-tae's choice.

1166
00:50:09,473 --> 00:50:14,044
<i>Let's begin the next round</i>
<i>with Sung-tae's ingredients.</i>

1167
00:50:14,111 --> 00:50:18,215
The two long-standing rivals,
Sam Kim and Choi Hyun-suk.

1168
00:50:18,281 --> 00:50:21,318
-The two original Italian chefs.
-Yes.

1169
00:50:21,385 --> 00:50:24,621
-And the order is for Italian cuisine.
-It is.

1170
00:50:24,688 --> 00:50:27,057
They've competed
against each other 11 times,

1171
00:50:27,124 --> 00:50:28,959
<i>and the current record is six to five.</i>

1172
00:50:29,026 --> 00:50:31,028
-Sam has the lead right now.
-That's close.

1173
00:50:31,094 --> 00:50:32,396
I didn't know.

1174
00:50:32,462 --> 00:50:34,131
You were winning.

1175
00:50:34,197 --> 00:50:36,900
-It's a big match.
-Yes, it really is.

1176
00:50:36,967 --> 00:50:40,604
Currently, Chef Hyun-suk has four stars.

1177
00:50:40,670 --> 00:50:44,241
-He had four rounds and won all four.
-Four wins.

1178
00:50:44,307 --> 00:50:46,243
He's on a roll right now.

1179
00:50:46,309 --> 00:50:48,211
Is there a secret to your success?

1180
00:50:48,278 --> 00:50:50,280
There's no special secret.

1181
00:50:50,347 --> 00:50:51,348
CHUCKLE

1182
00:50:51,415 --> 00:50:54,217
If I had one, it would be
to focus on the guest and not the star,

1183
00:50:54,284 --> 00:50:57,721
while cooking in my own style.

1184
00:50:57,788 --> 00:50:58,989
-I knew it.
-I see.

1185
00:50:59,056 --> 00:51:02,159
I don't have enough passion
to focus just on cooking.

1186
00:51:02,225 --> 00:51:05,662
I couldn't get distracted
by looking at the star.

1187
00:51:05,729 --> 00:51:07,731
Then my dish wouldn't be at 100%.

1188
00:51:07,798 --> 00:51:10,167
AN ALLERGIC REACTION
TO THE SHOW-OFF CHEF

1189
00:51:10,233 --> 00:51:13,737
Chef Hyun-suk's longest winning streak
in the history of the show was

1190
00:51:13,804 --> 00:51:15,705
five wins in a row.

1191
00:51:15,772 --> 00:51:18,708
-Oh…
-After today, it'll be five.

1192
00:51:18,775 --> 00:51:20,377
Wait a second.

1193
00:51:20,444 --> 00:51:22,512
I was simulating my recipe.
What did you say?

1194
00:51:22,579 --> 00:51:24,181
DR. SHOW-OFF CHEF'S
CHEF & MY FRIDGE MULTIVERSE

1195
00:51:24,247 --> 00:51:26,583
It's driving me crazy, jeez.

1196
00:51:26,650 --> 00:51:28,085
It's like watching a one-man play.

1197
00:51:28,652 --> 00:51:31,188
-Sung-jun is all ears.
-Yes.

1198
00:51:31,254 --> 00:51:33,123
-Does he seem cool to you?
-Yes.

1199
00:51:33,190 --> 00:51:34,624
Write it down.

1200
00:51:34,691 --> 00:51:37,360
-Is he making notes?
-He's learning everything.

1201
00:51:37,427 --> 00:51:40,497
But you're up against Sam Kim.

1202
00:51:40,564 --> 00:51:44,401
I can only see his pointy teeth,
and he's scaring me.

1203
00:51:44,468 --> 00:51:46,536
-Sung-tae mentioned that.
-Yes.

1204
00:51:46,603 --> 00:51:48,939
The worldwide villain
gave him his approval.

1205
00:51:49,005 --> 00:51:52,008
-Yes, the villain among chefs.
-Yes.

1206
00:51:52,075 --> 00:51:55,312
Last time, Chef Sam tried to fix the match

1207
00:51:55,378 --> 00:51:59,649
by offering Poong 500,000 won
and a bottle of olive oil.

1208
00:51:59,716 --> 00:52:02,519
I offered 500,000 won
and a bottle of extra virgin olive oil.

1209
00:52:02,586 --> 00:52:03,620
<i>Yes, right.</i>

1210
00:52:04,154 --> 00:52:05,522
<i>He must've said that for real.</i>

1211
00:52:05,589 --> 00:52:07,624
But this time, he made this request

1212
00:52:07,691 --> 00:52:08,758
-to our production crew.
-What is it?

1213
00:52:08,825 --> 00:52:11,928
"I want to know
Mr. Heo Sung-tae's bank account number."

1214
00:52:11,995 --> 00:52:16,199
-Oh, my gosh!
-How can he do this?

1215
00:52:16,266 --> 00:52:18,935
-Is this true?
-What's going on here?

1216
00:52:19,002 --> 00:52:22,005
He's trying
to pay his way into everything.

1217
00:52:22,072 --> 00:52:24,774
-I was just curious.
-He was curious.

1218
00:52:24,841 --> 00:52:26,476
Why do you want his bank information?

1219
00:52:26,543 --> 00:52:28,145
I don't know about everything else,

1220
00:52:28,211 --> 00:52:31,414
but I didn't want to lose
in a round titled Italian cuisine.

1221
00:52:31,481 --> 00:52:34,017
My roots are in Italian cuisine.

1222
00:52:34,084 --> 00:52:37,120
Chef Sam has done
Italian cuisine for 25 years now,

1223
00:52:37,187 --> 00:52:39,556
and I've been cooking for 30 years,

1224
00:52:39,623 --> 00:52:42,159
but among those years,
I spent 10 years in one restaurant.

1225
00:52:42,225 --> 00:52:46,096
-I spent 12 years in one restaurant.
-He spent 12 years.

1226
00:52:46,163 --> 00:52:48,532
-Two more years.
-I knew it. The pointy teeth.

1227
00:52:48,598 --> 00:52:51,801
-But you were the head chef for 12 years.
-Yes.

1228
00:52:51,868 --> 00:52:54,838
I started as the youngest chef

1229
00:52:54,905 --> 00:52:57,107
and made my way up for ten years.

1230
00:52:58,408 --> 00:53:01,111
-Sam was already established, right?
-He was established.

1231
00:53:01,178 --> 00:53:03,547
But you spent 10 years
including your apprentice years.

1232
00:53:03,613 --> 00:53:05,048
Which one is valued more highly?

1233
00:53:05,115 --> 00:53:08,318
-Of course, they're both amazing.
-Of course.

1234
00:53:08,385 --> 00:53:11,321
But it's not so easy
to remain in the field

1235
00:53:11,388 --> 00:53:14,491
for 12 years after his debut.

1236
00:53:14,558 --> 00:53:15,559
I knew it.

1237
00:53:15,625 --> 00:53:18,461
j-hope is siding with Sam.

1238
00:53:18,528 --> 00:53:21,464
It's amazing to keep this going
for 12 years after his debut.

1239
00:53:21,531 --> 00:53:25,302
-But I admire both.
-I knew it.

1240
00:53:26,236 --> 00:53:28,405
CHEF SAM'S INGREDIENTS:
CANNED WHOLE TOMATO, SPAGHETTI

1241
00:53:28,471 --> 00:53:30,640
PARSLEY, CANNED TUNA, OLIVE OIL,
TUNA SAUCE, WALNUT

1242
00:53:30,707 --> 00:53:32,409
The name of my dish is

1243
00:53:32,475 --> 00:53:35,078
Can't Say No to Tuna Pasta.

1244
00:53:35,145 --> 00:53:36,379
-Tuna?
-Yes.

1245
00:53:36,446 --> 00:53:39,382
-Can't Say No to Tuna Pasta?
-Yes.

1246
00:53:39,449 --> 00:53:42,953
He had canned tuna,

1247
00:53:43,019 --> 00:53:46,623
and this pasta is something
that Italian kids love.

1248
00:53:46,690 --> 00:53:51,595
I'm going to make that sauce
and serve it with pasta

1249
00:53:51,661 --> 00:53:53,230
<i>similar to </i>aglio e olio<i>.</i>

1250
00:53:53,296 --> 00:53:55,865
Sung-tae, have you ever had tuna pasta?

1251
00:53:55,932 --> 00:53:58,068
I've never even heard of it.

1252
00:53:58,134 --> 00:54:01,238
I recommend it to beginners
to Italian cuisine.

1253
00:54:01,304 --> 00:54:03,273
-I see.
-Thank you.

1254
00:54:04,207 --> 00:54:06,743
CHEF HYUN-SUK'S INGREDIENTS:

1255
00:54:06,810 --> 00:54:10,547
INSTANT MARSH CLAM SOUP,
FLOUR, OLIVE OIL

1256
00:54:10,614 --> 00:54:13,850
The Italian dish I'm making today is

1257
00:54:13,917 --> 00:54:16,987
-Heo-talian Vongole.
-Heo-talian?

1258
00:54:17,053 --> 00:54:19,990
-Heo-talian Vongole.
-Not Italian, but Heo-talian.

1259
00:54:20,056 --> 00:54:22,359
Heo Sung-tae plus Italian.

1260
00:54:22,425 --> 00:54:25,395
Vongole pasta is
one of my signature dishes too.

1261
00:54:25,462 --> 00:54:27,697
<i>I'll make pasta that looks like </i>sujebi

1262
00:54:27,764 --> 00:54:30,967
<i>and make a vongole pasta</i>
<i>that has unique texture.</i>

1263
00:54:31,034 --> 00:54:32,869
Wait, did he have clams?

1264
00:54:32,936 --> 00:54:34,971
-Clams?
-I didn't see any clams.

1265
00:54:35,038 --> 00:54:38,008
Clams are
the key ingredient to vongole pasta.

1266
00:54:38,074 --> 00:54:41,878
And Sung-tae's fridge already had
very delicious clam broth.

1267
00:54:41,945 --> 00:54:44,748
-The marsh clam soup?
-The clam broth.

1268
00:54:44,814 --> 00:54:47,284
I'll make vongole with marsh clam soup.

1269
00:54:47,350 --> 00:54:48,785
-Gosh.
-I'm looking forward to this

1270
00:54:48,852 --> 00:54:52,088
because he looked the most excited
when he saw that soup in the fridge.

1271
00:54:52,155 --> 00:54:54,090
-Yes, he looked happy.
-He went, "Whoa."

1272
00:54:54,157 --> 00:54:55,659
I was excited when I heard it too.

1273
00:54:55,725 --> 00:54:57,994
-The marsh clam soup.
-He's thrilled about that.

1274
00:54:58,061 --> 00:54:59,829
Your imagination surprised me.

1275
00:54:59,896 --> 00:55:03,900
I didn't expect him to use
the clam soup to do that.

1276
00:55:03,967 --> 00:55:08,305
I'll turn it into a new kind of vongole
so you won't remember the clam soup.

1277
00:55:08,371 --> 00:55:09,806
WHAT WILL THE VONGOLE PASTA
LOOK LIKE?

1278
00:55:09,873 --> 00:55:11,074
That sounds great.

1279
00:55:11,141 --> 00:55:15,545
Let us begin the round titled,
"Italian without leftovers."

1280
00:55:15,612 --> 00:55:18,014
This man is after five undefeated wins.

1281
00:55:18,081 --> 00:55:19,683
The show-off hero.

1282
00:55:19,749 --> 00:55:21,251
HAH!

1283
00:55:21,318 --> 00:55:22,986
Chef Choi Hyun-suk is up.

1284
00:55:23,053 --> 00:55:25,588
And this man is here
to break his undefeated record.

1285
00:55:25,655 --> 00:55:27,257
A villain with pointed teeth,

1286
00:55:27,324 --> 00:55:29,993
Chef Sam Kim is up against him.

1287
00:55:30,794 --> 00:55:32,996
This is a fight between two Italian chefs.

1288
00:55:33,063 --> 00:55:34,998
Who'll become the winner?

1289
00:55:35,065 --> 00:55:37,467
Let us begin

1290
00:55:37,534 --> 00:55:40,537
-the 15-minute cook-off!
-Let us begin!

1291
00:55:41,438 --> 00:55:45,675
THE TWO CHEFS WHO OPENED UP
CHEF & MY FRIDGE 11 YEARS AGO

1292
00:55:45,742 --> 00:55:48,278
It's a classic derby.

1293
00:55:48,345 --> 00:55:49,512
Choi Hyun-suk versus Sam Kim.

1294
00:55:50,447 --> 00:55:52,549
-He's using the marsh clam soup already.
-Marsh clams.

1295
00:55:52,615 --> 00:55:54,084
He's separating the broth.

1296
00:55:54,150 --> 00:55:57,921
Chef Hyun-suk, if you put water inside,
you'll see many more clams.

1297
00:55:57,987 --> 00:56:00,090
-There are more clams inside.
-In there?

1298
00:56:00,156 --> 00:56:03,293
-Every nook and cranny.
-He must like marsh clams.

1299
00:56:03,360 --> 00:56:06,663
The fridge owner wants him to use
every bit of the marsh clam soup.

1300
00:56:06,730 --> 00:56:09,466
I won't miss even one bit of marsh clam.

1301
00:56:10,233 --> 00:56:11,434
He won't miss it.

1302
00:56:12,001 --> 00:56:15,138
HE SHOWS OFF
AS OFTEN AS HE BREATHES

1303
00:56:15,205 --> 00:56:17,607
-He has to use it up.
-It was like a cosmetics ad.

1304
00:56:17,674 --> 00:56:19,976
-Yes.
-He has such a cheeky way of cooking.

1305
00:56:20,043 --> 00:56:21,444
He won't miss even one clam.

1306
00:56:21,511 --> 00:56:22,779
That's how I eat it.

1307
00:56:22,846 --> 00:56:26,249
I pour it inside,
then pour a bit of water to get the clams.

1308
00:56:26,316 --> 00:56:27,550
-You're saving it.
-You won't miss a single clam.

1309
00:56:27,617 --> 00:56:29,552
-You're saving it.
-You won't miss a single clam.

1310
00:56:29,619 --> 00:56:34,391
These two are
the legendary Italian cuisine rivals.

1311
00:56:34,457 --> 00:56:36,059
-He's using two pans.
-Two pans.

1312
00:56:36,126 --> 00:56:38,928
Hyun-suk spent ten years in one restaurant

1313
00:56:38,995 --> 00:56:40,597
but Sam spent 12 years!

1314
00:56:41,664 --> 00:56:44,067
1. STIR-FRY CHOPPED ONION
IN OLIVE OIL

1315
00:56:44,134 --> 00:56:47,103
If they're both making pasta,
it's a battle over pride

1316
00:56:47,170 --> 00:56:50,140
-as Italian chefs.
-It's a battle over pride.

1317
00:56:50,206 --> 00:56:53,243
The loser won't be able to sleep
for the next week.

1318
00:56:53,777 --> 00:56:55,645
HE BEGINS BY MAKING AGLIO E OLIO

1319
00:56:56,346 --> 00:56:59,182
HE CUTS UP LOTS OF GARLIC CLOVES
AND DROPS THEM IN OLIVE OIL!

1320
00:57:00,216 --> 00:57:01,418
CHILI PEPPER

1321
00:57:01,484 --> 00:57:03,253
2. OIL ANOTHER PAN

1322
00:57:03,319 --> 00:57:06,523
AND STIR-FRY GARLIC,
CHILI PEPPER AND PARSLEY

1323
00:57:06,589 --> 00:57:07,590
He's making pasta dough.

1324
00:57:07,657 --> 00:57:09,759
-The pasta dough.
-It's freshly made pasta.

1325
00:57:09,826 --> 00:57:11,261
-Fresh pasta.
-He's hand-making it.

1326
00:57:11,327 --> 00:57:16,566
He always gets the ratio perfect
with one try and one attempt.

1327
00:57:16,633 --> 00:57:18,201
He's making the pasta himself.

1328
00:57:18,268 --> 00:57:22,205
He's not making pasta, though.
That must be the <i>sujebi </i>dough.

1329
00:57:22,272 --> 00:57:23,873
Wait, did he put in an egg?

1330
00:57:23,940 --> 00:57:26,176
-No eggs. He's only using water.
-Only water?

1331
00:57:26,242 --> 00:57:29,179
Aren't you supposed to drop an egg
into pasta dough?

1332
00:57:29,245 --> 00:57:31,181
But he's making <i>sujebi</i>.

1333
00:57:31,247 --> 00:57:32,449
<i>Sujebi</i>!

1334
00:57:32,515 --> 00:57:34,684
People who had pasta with eggs were rich

1335
00:57:34,751 --> 00:57:37,620
-even in Italy.
-I see.

1336
00:57:37,687 --> 00:57:41,658
Ordinary people made pasta
with only water even in Italy.

1337
00:57:41,724 --> 00:57:43,560
A dish for an ordinary man.

1338
00:57:43,626 --> 00:57:45,728
But Sung-tae is rich.

1339
00:57:45,795 --> 00:57:46,830
What?

1340
00:57:46,896 --> 00:57:48,731
Wouldn't he want a rich man's dish?

1341
00:57:48,798 --> 00:57:50,366
-No.
-We should ask to find out.

1342
00:57:50,433 --> 00:57:54,737
I'll captivate Sung-tae
with a modest and humble dish.

1343
00:57:54,804 --> 00:57:56,005
He's very determined.

1344
00:57:56,072 --> 00:57:57,474
-Sung-tae.
-Yes?

1345
00:57:57,540 --> 00:58:00,710
Do you want a rich man's <i>sujebi</i>
or an ordinary man's <i>sujebi</i>?

1346
00:58:01,811 --> 00:58:02,979
A rich man's <i>sujebi</i>.

1347
00:58:04,948 --> 00:58:06,516
HE'S A WORLD-CLASS VILLAIN,
AFTER ALL

1348
00:58:06,583 --> 00:58:08,351
-He wants the rich man's <i>sujebi</i>.
-Rich man's <i>sujebi</i>.

1349
00:58:08,418 --> 00:58:10,920
-He said it!
-He'd want that when he came on this show.

1350
00:58:10,987 --> 00:58:14,891
But the texture will change a bit
if I add an egg to this.

1351
00:58:14,958 --> 00:58:16,259
Just do as you like.

1352
00:58:16,326 --> 00:58:17,794
He wasn't going to listen anyway.

1353
00:58:17,861 --> 00:58:20,930
-He had it planned from the start.
-Yes.

1354
00:58:20,997 --> 00:58:24,000
-But I like <i>sujebi </i>anyway.
-You do?

1355
00:58:24,067 --> 00:58:27,437
-He may have an advantage.
-So you like it.

1356
00:58:27,504 --> 00:58:28,872
What are you blending?

1357
00:58:28,938 --> 00:58:30,874
-He's blending green onion.
-He's blending green onion?

1358
00:58:30,940 --> 00:58:32,375
He's blending green onion?

1359
00:58:32,442 --> 00:58:34,143
-What about the texture?
-The dough might be green.

1360
00:58:34,210 --> 00:58:36,813
-Green dough?
-He already made the dough.

1361
00:58:36,880 --> 00:58:38,581
-He might make two types.
-Two types.

1362
00:58:38,648 --> 00:58:41,351
-Marsh clam soup is a bit green too.
-Really?

1363
00:58:41,417 --> 00:58:43,386
-The color.
-Like the soup.

1364
00:58:43,953 --> 00:58:45,555
HOW WILL THE COLOR TURN OUT?

1365
00:58:45,622 --> 00:58:48,658
You can make that color with green onion?
That's amazing.

1366
00:58:49,192 --> 00:58:50,660
There's tuna.

1367
00:58:51,494 --> 00:58:53,596
That's canned tuna.

1368
00:58:54,797 --> 00:58:56,599
That's canned tuna.

1369
00:58:56,666 --> 00:58:59,569
I want to try making Sam's dish at home.

1370
00:58:59,636 --> 00:59:01,371
It'll go so well together.

1371
00:59:02,872 --> 00:59:05,842
Tomato pasta with tuna?

1372
00:59:05,909 --> 00:59:08,044
Tuna pasta is always served with tomato.

1373
00:59:08,111 --> 00:59:09,612
Is that so?

1374
00:59:09,679 --> 00:59:12,615
Sung-tae, do you prefer
tomato pasta or cream pasta?

1375
00:59:12,682 --> 00:59:16,686
Sometimes I crave cream,
but sometimes I crave tomato.

1376
00:59:16,753 --> 00:59:17,987
It depends.

1377
00:59:18,054 --> 00:59:19,889
Tomato pasta is better for hangovers.

1378
00:59:19,956 --> 00:59:21,357
-Yes.
-What will he crave today?

1379
00:59:21,824 --> 00:59:22,825
TUNA SAUCE

1380
00:59:22,892 --> 00:59:26,296
Not only did he use canned tuna,
but he's also using tuna sauce.

1381
00:59:26,362 --> 00:59:27,363
Yes.

1382
00:59:29,032 --> 00:59:31,467
It's a neck-and-neck battle.

1383
00:59:31,534 --> 00:59:33,736
Yes, it's very tense.

1384
00:59:33,803 --> 00:59:35,872
HE BLENDS THE GREEN ONION JUICE
ONCE AGAIN

1385
00:59:35,939 --> 00:59:37,473
Gosh, it smells great.

1386
00:59:37,540 --> 00:59:39,375
I can smell it too.

1387
00:59:39,442 --> 00:59:42,412
-Look at that bright green color.
-I love the color.

1388
00:59:42,478 --> 00:59:44,881
-He's using it like coloring.
-Yes.

1389
00:59:44,948 --> 00:59:47,016
-I see.
-He's making two types of dough.

1390
00:59:47,784 --> 00:59:50,086
That was why he blended green onion.

1391
00:59:50,153 --> 00:59:51,487
He's now giving it color.

1392
00:59:51,554 --> 00:59:55,525
Is it like <i>kaljebi</i>?
Half <i>kalguksu</i>, half <i>sujebi</i>?

1393
00:59:55,592 --> 00:59:58,528
-Sung-tae wanted a rich man's vongole.
-Yes.

1394
01:00:00,196 --> 01:00:01,798
So I won't miss out on the presentation.

1395
01:00:02,899 --> 01:00:04,634
GOSH

1396
01:00:05,134 --> 01:00:07,337
MUTED LAUGHTER

1397
01:00:07,403 --> 01:00:09,472
-Did the pasta go in?
-Not yet.

1398
01:00:10,540 --> 01:00:12,575
SAM KIM USES DRY PASTA

1399
01:00:12,642 --> 01:00:15,545
6. BOIL SPAGHETTI
IN BOILING WATER

1400
01:00:16,279 --> 01:00:19,649
7. ADD TUNA SAUCE AND PARSLEY
INTO TUNA RAGÙ AND BRING TO A BOIL

1401
01:00:20,617 --> 01:00:21,551
EYES WIDE OPEN

1402
01:00:21,618 --> 01:00:23,419
THE GREEN DOUGH IS DONE!

1403
01:00:23,920 --> 01:00:25,154
AMAZED

1404
01:00:25,955 --> 01:00:27,657
The dough looks perfect.

1405
01:00:28,791 --> 01:00:29,959
HE BEGINS TO KNEAD THE DOUGH!

1406
01:00:30,026 --> 01:00:33,830
-He's kneading the dough now.
-Hyun-suk kneads the dough.

1407
01:00:33,896 --> 01:00:35,565
It's amazing how he does that in one try.

1408
01:00:35,632 --> 01:00:36,866
Yes, that's amazing.

1409
01:00:36,933 --> 01:00:39,435
-It looks easy, but it's hard.
-It's hard.

1410
01:00:39,502 --> 01:00:42,305
People usually go back and forth,
adding flour and water.

1411
01:00:42,372 --> 01:00:44,474
It's not easy to reach that texture.

1412
01:00:44,540 --> 01:00:46,409
Look at that color.

1413
01:00:48,244 --> 01:00:50,647
"Su" in <i>sujebi </i>means hand,
so it's usually hand-pulled,

1414
01:00:50,713 --> 01:00:52,615
but he's rolling it with a pin.

1415
01:00:52,682 --> 01:00:54,884
-He'll roll it first, I guess.
-He'll probably do it after.

1416
01:00:56,252 --> 01:00:58,855
Using a pin means you're making pin-jebi.

1417
01:00:58,921 --> 01:01:01,958
-Pin-jebi?
-You must use your hands to make <i>sujebi</i>.

1418
01:01:02,025 --> 01:01:03,960
-Pin-jebi?
-Pin-jebi?

1419
01:01:04,027 --> 01:01:06,229
I like the sound of that word. Pin-jebi.

1420
01:01:06,295 --> 01:01:11,234
He refuses to answer
when the question doesn't benefit him.

1421
01:01:11,300 --> 01:01:12,902
You've known him for a long time.

1422
01:01:12,969 --> 01:01:14,470
I was too focused.

1423
01:01:18,174 --> 01:01:20,743
He always says he's focused.

1424
01:01:20,810 --> 01:01:22,645
He's focused when in disadvantage.

1425
01:01:23,646 --> 01:01:24,981
Why is he spraying that?

1426
01:01:25,581 --> 01:01:27,417
Why are you spraying that?

1427
01:01:27,483 --> 01:01:29,218
Is he trying to layer those?

1428
01:01:29,285 --> 01:01:30,653
CORRECT

1429
01:01:30,720 --> 01:01:34,223
-He layered the doughs.
-My gosh.

1430
01:01:34,290 --> 01:01:35,692
He's giving it two colors.

1431
01:01:36,259 --> 01:01:39,295
It'll show two colors
when he presses on that.

1432
01:01:39,362 --> 01:01:42,031
-He's rolling it.
-He's rolling it up.

1433
01:01:42,098 --> 01:01:45,268
He layered two doughs
and began to roll it up.

1434
01:01:45,334 --> 01:01:47,270
I think he'll cut it.

1435
01:01:47,336 --> 01:01:50,640
-He'll cut it and press it.
-Like noodles?

1436
01:01:50,707 --> 01:01:51,708
My gosh.

1437
01:01:51,774 --> 01:01:55,078
-It's pretty like a roll cake.
-It is.

1438
01:01:55,144 --> 01:01:56,713
It looks so pretty.

1439
01:01:56,779 --> 01:01:57,947
It's like a lollipop.

1440
01:01:58,014 --> 01:02:02,118
Everyone is watching Hyun-suk.

1441
01:02:02,185 --> 01:02:04,253
Oh, no. Show your pointy teeth.

1442
01:02:04,320 --> 01:02:07,056
Sam is just doing things
as he always does.

1443
01:02:07,123 --> 01:02:09,025
Yes, I'm always the same.

1444
01:02:09,092 --> 01:02:11,761
Yes, are those walnuts?

1445
01:02:11,828 --> 01:02:14,330
-Yes, walnuts.
-Walnuts must be important.

1446
01:02:14,397 --> 01:02:16,265
Walnuts in pasta?

1447
01:02:16,332 --> 01:02:18,234
That looks so pretty.

1448
01:02:18,301 --> 01:02:21,104
-He already captured the attention.
-Look at the color.

1449
01:02:21,170 --> 01:02:23,339
It looks like that thing in cup noodles.

1450
01:02:23,406 --> 01:02:25,308
THIS THING?

1451
01:02:25,374 --> 01:02:27,043
-The fish cake?
-The fish cake?

1452
01:02:27,110 --> 01:02:29,178
-In Yukgaejang?
-Yukgaejang.

1453
01:02:29,245 --> 01:02:30,546
It looks pretty.

1454
01:02:30,613 --> 01:02:32,281
Do you like that shape, Sung-tae?

1455
01:02:32,348 --> 01:02:34,917
-Yes, I love it.
-You do.

1456
01:02:34,984 --> 01:02:36,385
He loves it.

1457
01:02:36,452 --> 01:02:40,289
Sung-tae is captivated
as he watches him cook.

1458
01:02:40,356 --> 01:02:42,325
So far, when it comes to the presentation,

1459
01:02:42,391 --> 01:02:45,328
-Chef Hyun-suk has an overwhelming win.
-Yes.

1460
01:02:45,928 --> 01:02:47,063
THERE IT IS!

1461
01:02:48,664 --> 01:02:50,800
Hyun-suk sprinkles flour on the floor!

1462
01:02:50,867 --> 01:02:53,069
HE SEALS PEOPLE'S ATTENTION
WITH HIS SIGNATURE MOVE!

1463
01:02:53,636 --> 01:02:56,606
-There it is.
-That was what I wanted to see.

1464
01:02:56,672 --> 01:02:57,874
The man who sprinkles flour.

1465
01:02:57,940 --> 01:03:00,309
-I wanted to see him sprinkle salt.
-And you did.

1466
01:03:00,376 --> 01:03:02,912
-Yes, I got a good look.
-You did.

1467
01:03:03,679 --> 01:03:05,648
ON THE OTHER HAND, SAM KIM
STILL HIDES HIS POINTY TEETH

1468
01:03:05,715 --> 01:03:08,851
Sam Kim is now making tuna pasta.

1469
01:03:08,918 --> 01:03:11,354
He's focusing only on the flavor.

1470
01:03:11,420 --> 01:03:14,390
So is the sauce basically tomato sauce?

1471
01:03:14,457 --> 01:03:16,592
It is tomato sauce.

1472
01:03:16,659 --> 01:03:19,295
<i>But in Italy, there's a sauce</i>
<i>called </i>colatura di alici<i>.</i>

1473
01:03:19,362 --> 01:03:21,697
<i>There are pasta dishes</i>
<i>that use anchovy sauce.</i>

1474
01:03:21,764 --> 01:03:23,833
<i>I took the idea from that.</i>

1475
01:03:23,900 --> 01:03:25,768
I needed some Parmesan cheese,

1476
01:03:25,835 --> 01:03:27,637
but I seasoned everything
with fish sauce instead.

1477
01:03:28,738 --> 01:03:31,507
j-hope had a lot of Parmesan
in his fridge.

1478
01:03:31,574 --> 01:03:35,077
-He had lots of cheese packets.
-Should I give him some?

1479
01:03:35,144 --> 01:03:36,412
SHOULD I GIVE HIM
HOPE AMENITIES(?)

1480
01:03:36,479 --> 01:03:38,381
-I can always give it to you.
-What a shame.

1481
01:03:39,215 --> 01:03:43,319
He's making a dish inspired
by anchovy pasta from Italy.

1482
01:03:43,386 --> 01:03:46,556
We haven't seen what it's like yet.

1483
01:03:46,622 --> 01:03:48,291
You have 6 minutes and 30 seconds.

1484
01:03:48,357 --> 01:03:49,992
-He's chopping garlic cloves.
-Yes.

1485
01:03:50,059 --> 01:03:51,928
It's been more than six minutes.

1486
01:03:51,994 --> 01:03:53,763
It's time to speed up.

1487
01:03:53,830 --> 01:03:55,398
Sylvia is still resting.

1488
01:03:55,464 --> 01:03:58,034
-Yes, Sylvia. My Sylvia!
-It's not doing anything.

1489
01:03:58,100 --> 01:04:01,404
-Was Sylvia neglected? No, it's not.
-Sylvia.

1490
01:04:01,470 --> 01:04:04,473
Hyun-suk uses Sylvia
as soon as we bring it up.

1491
01:04:04,540 --> 01:04:07,043
There's this thing
called the Curse of Sylvia.

1492
01:04:07,109 --> 01:04:09,445
You have six minutes left.

1493
01:04:09,512 --> 01:04:12,648
He just put in garlic.
He didn't forget it this time.

1494
01:04:17,587 --> 01:04:19,222
WHAT'S HE SAYING?

1495
01:04:19,288 --> 01:04:21,357
Is he in a hurry?

1496
01:04:21,424 --> 01:04:24,427
This time, he didn't forget the garlic
when making vongole.

1497
01:04:24,493 --> 01:04:26,929
-No.
-He put in a lot.

1498
01:04:26,996 --> 01:04:29,532
-But it's noodles.
-Yes.

1499
01:04:29,599 --> 01:04:31,901
-Six minutes.
-Whoever that ends first…

1500
01:04:31,968 --> 01:04:34,604
-Will be at an advantage.
-And better texture.

1501
01:04:35,805 --> 01:04:38,007
-He only used garlic.
-The <i>sujebi</i>.

1502
01:04:38,074 --> 01:04:40,243
-The <i>sujebi</i>.
-Yes.

1503
01:04:40,309 --> 01:04:42,812
The color will be prettier
once they're cooked.

1504
01:04:42,879 --> 01:04:44,113
I can't wait to see it.

1505
01:04:44,180 --> 01:04:47,483
-The walnuts are done.
-He got those out.

1506
01:04:47,550 --> 01:04:49,352
-How will he use those?
-The marsh clam soup goes in.

1507
01:04:49,418 --> 01:04:50,720
-Whoa.
-Whoa.

1508
01:04:50,786 --> 01:04:52,288
The marsh clam soup goes in.

1509
01:04:55,358 --> 01:04:58,461
9. BOIL MARSH CLAM SOUP
IN THE PAN WITH GARLIC

1510
01:04:58,527 --> 01:04:59,862
-Whoa.
-Whoa.

1511
01:04:59,929 --> 01:05:02,999
He does that right away
just as we talked about walnuts.

1512
01:05:03,065 --> 01:05:04,600
"Look at me."

1513
01:05:04,667 --> 01:05:06,702
-The fire show.
-Hyun-suk begins a fire show.

1514
01:05:06,769 --> 01:05:09,572
He's now working with Sylvia.

1515
01:05:09,639 --> 01:05:11,474
-Five minutes.
-Five minutes.

1516
01:05:11,540 --> 01:05:12,708
Why don't you grind it?

1517
01:05:12,775 --> 01:05:14,510
-Sung-tae marked five minutes.
-Five minutes.

1518
01:05:14,577 --> 01:05:16,345
On the dot.

1519
01:05:16,412 --> 01:05:19,048
-I have to get out there. I'll go.
-Go.

1520
01:05:19,115 --> 01:05:21,450
Sung-tae marked five minutes
and asked me to go.

1521
01:05:21,517 --> 01:05:22,818
I can't believe this.

1522
01:05:22,885 --> 01:05:24,654
HE FINALLY HAD SOME ATTENTION
WITH THE WALNUTS

1523
01:05:24,720 --> 01:05:26,522
He's cutting the walnuts.

1524
01:05:26,589 --> 01:05:27,590
Why don't you grind it?

1525
01:05:27,657 --> 01:05:29,258
It's like El Classico.

1526
01:05:29,325 --> 01:05:31,327
The long-standing rivals, a classic match.

1527
01:05:31,394 --> 01:05:33,996
-Try something.
-A lot is going on.

1528
01:05:34,063 --> 01:05:37,233
Many things are under way right now.

1529
01:05:37,300 --> 01:05:39,235
9. MIX SPAGHETTI WITH GARLIC
SAUCE TO FINISH AGLIO E OLIO

1530
01:05:39,302 --> 01:05:41,370
-The pasta goes in.
-The pasta is in.

1531
01:05:41,437 --> 01:05:43,172
-I hope he leaves no leftovers.
-The pasta goes in.

1532
01:05:43,239 --> 01:05:45,007
He's making <i>sujebi</i>.

1533
01:05:45,074 --> 01:05:47,543
-What's this?
-Tuna.

1534
01:05:47,610 --> 01:05:49,045
-May I try it?
-Sure.

1535
01:05:49,111 --> 01:05:51,814
This is the sauce
that will go under the pasta.

1536
01:05:51,881 --> 01:05:53,616
-The sauce?
-The sauce.

1537
01:05:53,683 --> 01:05:55,952
-The sauce under the pasta.
-The tuna sauce?

1538
01:05:56,018 --> 01:05:58,454
The sauce is important.

1539
01:05:58,521 --> 01:06:00,790
How is it?

1540
01:06:01,357 --> 01:06:04,527
HOW IS THE TUNA SAUCE
HE WORKED SO HARD TO MAKE?

1541
01:06:06,462 --> 01:06:09,532
It tastes bland!

1542
01:06:09,598 --> 01:06:10,967
THE FAN'S HEART IS SHAKEN UP

1543
01:06:11,033 --> 01:06:12,902
-It's still bland.
-Has he not seasoned it yet?

1544
01:06:12,969 --> 01:06:14,103
Does he need more sauce?

1545
01:06:14,170 --> 01:06:15,604
I think you need more salt.

1546
01:06:15,671 --> 01:06:17,306
-He's adding fish sauce.
-That's it.

1547
01:06:17,373 --> 01:06:19,208
-I told you so.
-He has a good sense of taste.

1548
01:06:19,275 --> 01:06:21,510
Yes, I have an excellent sense of taste.

1549
01:06:21,577 --> 01:06:24,246
-Try that one.
-Let's see. This one.

1550
01:06:24,914 --> 01:06:28,184
-The <i>sujebi</i>.
-Hyun-suk scoops the <i>sujebi </i>out.

1551
01:06:28,250 --> 01:06:30,386
-I love the color.
-The color is so pretty.

1552
01:06:30,453 --> 01:06:31,620
You're right.

1553
01:06:31,687 --> 01:06:33,856
This will probably be the pasta sauce.

1554
01:06:33,923 --> 01:06:35,391
It's so pretty.

1555
01:06:35,458 --> 01:06:37,326
HE WANTS TO PUT THE SPOON IN

1556
01:06:37,393 --> 01:06:38,594
He won't let him taste it.

1557
01:06:38,661 --> 01:06:40,262
-Let me try it.
-He has to wait.

1558
01:06:40,329 --> 01:06:41,530
You need to wait.

1559
01:06:42,398 --> 01:06:44,033
Try it now.

1560
01:06:44,100 --> 01:06:47,937
-What was that?
-It's like training a dog.

1561
01:06:48,004 --> 01:06:49,105
Come on.

1562
01:06:49,171 --> 01:06:50,506
JOTTING DOWN WHATEVER'S COOL

1563
01:06:50,573 --> 01:06:51,974
-It's hot.
-That was cool.

1564
01:06:52,908 --> 01:06:54,710
-There's a lot of garlic in here.
-Garlic.

1565
01:06:54,777 --> 01:06:57,446
Does it taste like vongole?

1566
01:06:58,681 --> 01:07:00,182
What's it like?

1567
01:07:02,651 --> 01:07:03,853
GULPING

1568
01:07:03,919 --> 01:07:06,756
I personally hope it's a bit spicier.

1569
01:07:06,822 --> 01:07:08,924
-I see.
-A little more spiciness.

1570
01:07:08,991 --> 01:07:10,626
-A bit spicier.
-It'll become blander

1571
01:07:10,693 --> 01:07:14,597
-once the <i>sujebi </i>goes in.
-That can happen.

1572
01:07:14,663 --> 01:07:16,332
Can you salt it a little?

1573
01:07:16,399 --> 01:07:17,833
Shouldn't you add some spiciness?

1574
01:07:17,900 --> 01:07:19,568
-Don't you need salt?
-I don't.

1575
01:07:19,635 --> 01:07:22,405
He'll keep this as is.

1576
01:07:22,471 --> 01:07:24,006
It looks so pretty.

1577
01:07:25,307 --> 01:07:27,676
Sam is looking busy too.

1578
01:07:27,743 --> 01:07:28,944
There are 2 minutes and 50 seconds left.

1579
01:07:29,011 --> 01:07:31,047
-Yes.
-There are 2 minutes and 50 seconds.

1580
01:07:31,113 --> 01:07:32,581
AGAIN, OLIVE OIL

1581
01:07:32,648 --> 01:07:35,284
He'll keep this as is.

1582
01:07:35,351 --> 01:07:36,585
Sam is looking busy too.

1583
01:07:36,652 --> 01:07:39,688
Why did he crush walnuts?

1584
01:07:39,755 --> 01:07:41,190
I want to know what it'll do.

1585
01:07:41,257 --> 01:07:42,992
Yes, and he's starting to serve it.

1586
01:07:43,059 --> 01:07:45,895
As I mentioned,
it'll be advantageous to finish first.

1587
01:07:45,961 --> 01:07:48,130
-That's important.
-And the amount is important.

1588
01:07:48,197 --> 01:07:49,598
Italian without leftovers.

1589
01:07:49,665 --> 01:07:52,768
Hey, this smells awesome too.

1590
01:07:52,835 --> 01:07:54,804
It's better to move quickly.
Are you serving the pasta?

1591
01:07:54,870 --> 01:07:58,441
If they both taste good,
the first person may win.

1592
01:07:58,507 --> 01:07:59,975
He's not mixing it with the pasta.

1593
01:08:00,042 --> 01:08:01,644
That looks so pretty.

1594
01:08:01,710 --> 01:08:03,646
-I see. It's served separately.
-Separately.

1595
01:08:03,712 --> 01:08:05,514
-It looks so pretty.
-Two minutes.

1596
01:08:05,581 --> 01:08:07,650
-It smells so good.
-Sam, it's so pretty.

1597
01:08:07,716 --> 01:08:09,618
That's how he's using it.

1598
01:08:09,685 --> 01:08:10,920
10. PUT TUNA RAGÙ ON THE DISH

1599
01:08:10,986 --> 01:08:12,621
AND TOP IT
WITH AGLIO E OLIO AND WALNUT

1600
01:08:12,688 --> 01:08:15,558
If Sung-tae leaves leftovers,
it means you lose.

1601
01:08:16,826 --> 01:08:19,829
11. STIR-FRY MARSH CLAMS
IN MARSH CLAM SAUCE,

1602
01:08:19,895 --> 01:08:21,030
SERVE OVER SUJEBI

1603
01:08:21,096 --> 01:08:22,131
Two minutes.

1604
01:08:23,365 --> 01:08:24,500
It smells so good.

1605
01:08:24,567 --> 01:08:26,735
Hyun-suk begins to serve his dish too!

1606
01:08:26,802 --> 01:08:28,070
-It's pretty.
-Look how focused he is.

1607
01:08:28,137 --> 01:08:29,772
-It's so pretty.
-Parsley.

1608
01:08:29,839 --> 01:08:32,174
Choi Hyun-suk rings the bell!

1609
01:08:32,241 --> 01:08:33,242
Hyun-suk is done.

1610
01:08:33,309 --> 01:08:36,045
Gosh, he still had
2 minutes and 10 seconds.

1611
01:08:36,112 --> 01:08:38,180
He finished up so early.

1612
01:08:38,247 --> 01:08:40,282
Gosh, Hyun-suk.

1613
01:08:40,349 --> 01:08:42,918
Then it'll be better
to use all two minutes.

1614
01:08:42,985 --> 01:08:44,753
-Yes.
-Yes, you're second anyway.

1615
01:08:44,820 --> 01:08:46,722
You can relax as you finish up.

1616
01:08:46,789 --> 01:08:48,457
TOPPING THE PASTA
WITH GARLIC AND CRUSHED WALNUT

1617
01:08:48,524 --> 01:08:50,793
He topped this with walnut.

1618
01:08:50,860 --> 01:08:52,228
Sam Kim is done too.

1619
01:08:52,294 --> 01:08:54,497
-That was so fast.
-He has 1 minute and 40 seconds left.

1620
01:08:54,563 --> 01:08:57,032
You had 1 minute and 39.24 seconds left.

1621
01:08:57,099 --> 01:09:00,169
-They both had time left.
-The two strong contenders.

1622
01:09:00,236 --> 01:09:03,272
They were cooking so quickly.

1623
01:09:03,339 --> 01:09:05,708
Gosh, those look so good.

1624
01:09:05,774 --> 01:09:07,576
Look at the color. It's insane.

1625
01:09:07,643 --> 01:09:10,880
Gosh, they both look amazing.

1626
01:09:10,946 --> 01:09:14,416
-It was a bit bland before. Is it okay?
-It looks amazing.

1627
01:09:14,483 --> 01:09:15,484
Whoa.

1628
01:09:15,551 --> 01:09:17,653
Does Sung-tae enjoy less strong taste?

1629
01:09:17,720 --> 01:09:21,624
-He'll try Chef Hyun-suk's dish first.
-Okay.

1630
01:09:22,124 --> 01:09:25,895
A RENDEZVOUS OF PRETTY SUJEBI
AND MARSH CLAM SOUP

1631
01:09:27,363 --> 01:09:31,033
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S
HEO-TALIAN VONGOLE

1632
01:09:31,100 --> 01:09:32,334
It looks good.

1633
01:09:32,401 --> 01:09:35,070
He holds his spoon tightly.

1634
01:09:35,137 --> 01:09:37,606
Sung-tae has high hopes.

1635
01:09:37,673 --> 01:09:39,742
-He's like an excited kid.
-It looks amazing.

1636
01:09:39,808 --> 01:09:41,544
Yes, this is Heo-talian Vongole.

1637
01:09:41,610 --> 01:09:43,846
-It's so pretty.
-Isn't it?

1638
01:09:43,913 --> 01:09:46,248
How did he do this with marsh clams?

1639
01:09:46,315 --> 01:09:48,150
-It looks so pretty.
-It looks good.

1640
01:09:48,217 --> 01:09:50,819
-Can he just eat it like this?
-Yes, feel free to dig in.

1641
01:09:51,387 --> 01:09:53,455
-Heo-talian Vongole.
-It's so pretty.

1642
01:09:53,522 --> 01:09:55,324
First and foremost, it's pretty.

1643
01:09:56,091 --> 01:09:57,726
It doesn't remind me
of the marsh clam soup.

1644
01:09:57,793 --> 01:09:59,428
It doesn't remind him of the soup,

1645
01:09:59,495 --> 01:10:00,596
although he used two packs.

1646
01:10:00,663 --> 01:10:02,798
He has the soup often,
but it doesn't taste like it.

1647
01:10:02,865 --> 01:10:04,567
I wonder
what the texture of <i>sujebi </i>is like.

1648
01:10:04,633 --> 01:10:07,303
What's it like?
Is it like the usual <i>sujebi </i>we know?

1649
01:10:08,103 --> 01:10:10,773
The texture is completely different,
and it must be the green onion.

1650
01:10:10,839 --> 01:10:13,209
I can smell it too.

1651
01:10:13,275 --> 01:10:14,977
-It's rather unique.
-Is it?

1652
01:10:15,044 --> 01:10:16,779
-It'll smell like green onion.
-He blended it.

1653
01:10:16,845 --> 01:10:18,747
I used the blender

1654
01:10:18,814 --> 01:10:21,217
because it'll act like kneading

1655
01:10:21,283 --> 01:10:23,953
and make the dough very chewy.

1656
01:10:24,019 --> 01:10:26,121
It'll feel much chewier than you think.

1657
01:10:26,689 --> 01:10:28,791
He took his third bite!

1658
01:10:28,857 --> 01:10:32,061
-He's devouring it.
-Another important thing is that

1659
01:10:32,127 --> 01:10:35,598
he can't feel sick of it
after a few bites.

1660
01:10:35,664 --> 01:10:39,168
His lips are
almost about to touch the dish.

1661
01:10:39,235 --> 01:10:41,437
-He won't miss even a drop of sauce.
-No.

1662
01:10:41,503 --> 01:10:43,105
That's amazing.

1663
01:10:43,172 --> 01:10:47,443
<i>Next, Chef Sam's</i>
<i>Can't Say No to Tuna Pasta.</i>

1664
01:10:48,410 --> 01:10:52,348
CHEF SAM KIM'S
CAN'T SAY NO TO TUNA PASTA

1665
01:10:52,414 --> 01:10:54,650
You should mix it up with the sauce
at the very bottom.

1666
01:10:54,717 --> 01:10:56,552
-Can't Say No to Tuna Pasta.
-Pasta is…

1667
01:10:56,619 --> 01:10:58,821
He's almost chugging it down.

1668
01:10:58,887 --> 01:11:00,522
I wonder what it's like.

1669
01:11:01,090 --> 01:11:02,091
SLURP

1670
01:11:03,392 --> 01:11:04,393
He's almost chugging it down.

1671
01:11:04,460 --> 01:11:06,528
-He eats heartily.
-Yes.

1672
01:11:06,595 --> 01:11:10,566
-I can't tell by his face.
-It's hard to read his facial expression.

1673
01:11:10,633 --> 01:11:13,369
How did he make a dish taste like this
with fish sauce?

1674
01:11:13,435 --> 01:11:15,104
How did he do this with fish sauce?

1675
01:11:15,170 --> 01:11:18,674
Fish sauce is salty,
and it adds umami too.

1676
01:11:18,741 --> 01:11:20,876
<i>It adds that flavor.</i>

1677
01:11:20,943 --> 01:11:23,846
-Is it your first time eating tuna pasta?
-Yes.

1678
01:11:23,912 --> 01:11:25,914
It's new and appealing.

1679
01:11:25,981 --> 01:11:28,951
-It's really good.
-Is it?

1680
01:11:29,018 --> 01:11:32,588
Watching him eat is making me hungry.

1681
01:11:32,655 --> 01:11:34,990
-You like Italian cuisine.
-You do.

1682
01:11:35,057 --> 01:11:38,494
These dishes are on a different level

1683
01:11:38,560 --> 01:11:41,964
-compared to what I had before.
-On another level.

1684
01:11:42,031 --> 01:11:45,634
<i>Chef Hyun-suk's dish had</i>
<i>the cleanest taste,</i>

1685
01:11:45,701 --> 01:11:47,736
whereas Chef Sam's pasta had

1686
01:11:47,803 --> 01:11:49,705
<i>the most piquant taste.</i>

1687
01:11:49,772 --> 01:11:52,408
<i>-The most piquant.</i>
<i>-The most piquant.</i>

1688
01:11:52,474 --> 01:11:55,978
-I enjoyed it very much.
-Yes, that's it for now.

1689
01:11:56,045 --> 01:11:58,047
Okay, first,

1690
01:11:58,113 --> 01:12:02,251
-let's try Heo-talian Vongole.
-Okay.

1691
01:12:03,319 --> 01:12:05,120
SAVORING

1692
01:12:06,588 --> 01:12:07,589
AMAZED

1693
01:12:08,991 --> 01:12:11,860
It's almost irritatingly delicious.

1694
01:12:11,927 --> 01:12:14,029
It doesn't taste like marsh clam soup.

1695
01:12:14,096 --> 01:12:16,498
-It's seasoned perfectly.
-Yes.

1696
01:12:16,565 --> 01:12:18,367
It was bland before.

1697
01:12:18,434 --> 01:12:21,704
You can taste years of experience in this.
It's seasoned perfectly.

1698
01:12:21,770 --> 01:12:22,771
It's so good.

1699
01:12:22,838 --> 01:12:26,241
The marsh clam soup
already has that salty flavor.

1700
01:12:26,308 --> 01:12:27,476
My gosh.

1701
01:12:28,277 --> 01:12:31,280
This is just amazing.

1702
01:12:31,347 --> 01:12:33,782
I'm not sure if I can say this,

1703
01:12:33,849 --> 01:12:36,352
but this was my personal best today.

1704
01:12:37,619 --> 01:12:38,821
HEH

1705
01:12:38,887 --> 01:12:41,090
-This is hilarious.
-Touché to all chefs.

1706
01:12:41,156 --> 01:12:42,758
But I agree.

1707
01:12:42,825 --> 01:12:45,527
-I enjoyed everyone's dish…
-Yes.

1708
01:12:45,594 --> 01:12:48,297
…but everything about this
is just my type.

1709
01:12:48,364 --> 01:12:51,500
I want to hear from Chef Jong-won.

1710
01:12:52,434 --> 01:12:53,769
-Who?
-Jong-won.

1711
01:12:53,836 --> 01:12:55,170
He's glaring at me.

1712
01:12:55,237 --> 01:12:56,705
-Look in front of me.
-Jong-won?

1713
01:12:56,772 --> 01:12:59,041
I like to pick up good habits.

1714
01:12:59,808 --> 01:13:03,512
He's showing off his table
because he cleaned it neatly.

1715
01:13:03,579 --> 01:13:05,948
-His counter is spick and span.
-It is.

1716
01:13:06,014 --> 01:13:09,718
I got chills when I saw him
layering and cutting

1717
01:13:09,785 --> 01:13:12,087
the <i>sujebi </i>dough.

1718
01:13:12,154 --> 01:13:15,124
I thought it was my thing
to make pretty dishes.

1719
01:13:15,190 --> 01:13:17,493
I thought, "Expected no less
from Chef Hyun-suk."

1720
01:13:17,559 --> 01:13:21,330
<i>Sujebi</i> can become too soggy
if you don't cook it right.

1721
01:13:21,397 --> 01:13:26,635
It was chewy and delicious,
and he made it al dente without eggs.

1722
01:13:26,702 --> 01:13:28,103
My goodness.

1723
01:13:28,170 --> 01:13:29,671
-He's that skillful.
-Yes.

1724
01:13:30,239 --> 01:13:31,774
-It was great.
-Yes.

1725
01:13:31,840 --> 01:13:36,345
Next, Chef Sam's dish.

1726
01:13:36,412 --> 01:13:39,214
Gosh, it smells amazing.

1727
01:13:39,281 --> 01:13:41,884
I can't decide.

1728
01:13:41,950 --> 01:13:44,887
These dishes are two polar opposites.

1729
01:13:45,888 --> 01:13:47,523
HE PICKS UP HIS DISHES
AND BEGINS TO DEVOUR

1730
01:13:47,589 --> 01:13:48,857
It's such an honor.

1731
01:13:48,924 --> 01:13:50,626
-j-hope finished it.
-He's done.

1732
01:13:50,692 --> 01:13:52,961
I don't think I can decide

1733
01:13:53,028 --> 01:13:56,932
which one of these was better.

1734
01:13:56,999 --> 01:13:59,301
-Is that walnut on the top?
-Yes.

1735
01:13:59,368 --> 01:14:01,036
-I loved that texture.
-Yes!

1736
01:14:01,103 --> 01:14:03,739
It adds a nice twist.

1737
01:14:03,806 --> 01:14:06,341
It wasn't boring to eat.

1738
01:14:06,408 --> 01:14:11,580
<i>When I had this, I thought,</i>
<i>"How can it be so chewy and delicious?"</i>

1739
01:14:11,647 --> 01:14:15,784
<i>But this one had a great balance</i>
<i>with interesting texture,</i>

1740
01:14:15,851 --> 01:14:18,320
making the experience never boring.

1741
01:14:18,387 --> 01:14:21,757
The aglio e olio-style pasta
made with fish sauce,

1742
01:14:21,824 --> 01:14:23,859
the tanginess of tomato,

1743
01:14:23,926 --> 01:14:26,028
and the sweet onion.

1744
01:14:26,094 --> 01:14:29,731
In the end, the nutty walnut adds
one final touch

1745
01:14:29,798 --> 01:14:32,301
to make the four come in harmony.

1746
01:14:32,367 --> 01:14:34,403
The flavor is so skillfully balanced.

1747
01:14:34,470 --> 01:14:36,638
Between Brad Pitt

1748
01:14:36,705 --> 01:14:40,375
and George Clooney,
who am I going to choose?

1749
01:14:40,442 --> 01:14:43,879
-That's a perfect analogy.
-Let's say I want to go on a date.

1750
01:14:43,946 --> 01:14:46,415
This is Brad Pitt,

1751
01:14:46,482 --> 01:14:49,952
-and this is George Clooney.
-Sam is George Clooney,

1752
01:14:50,018 --> 01:14:51,987
and Hyun-suk is Brad Pitt.

1753
01:14:52,554 --> 01:14:55,491
Sung-tae, it's time to decide.

1754
01:14:55,557 --> 01:14:57,526
Press one for Sam Kim,

1755
01:14:57,593 --> 01:14:59,495
and press two for Choi Hyun-suk.

1756
01:14:59,561 --> 01:15:03,365
Please make your decision
and press the button!

1757
01:15:03,432 --> 01:15:04,633
Press it.

1758
01:15:04,700 --> 01:15:07,336
Yes, he's having a tough time.

1759
01:15:08,103 --> 01:15:10,105
-Did you push it? He did.
-Yes.

1760
01:15:10,172 --> 01:15:12,875
Who did Sung-tae choose?

1761
01:15:12,941 --> 01:15:15,244
Let's find out the result.

1762
01:15:15,310 --> 01:15:18,480
The order was,
"Italian without leftovers."

1763
01:15:18,547 --> 01:15:20,916
Choi Hyun-suk is aiming for his fifth win,

1764
01:15:20,983 --> 01:15:24,419
and Sam Kim is still in the lead
between the two.

1765
01:15:24,486 --> 01:15:26,922
This is the first round in this season

1766
01:15:26,989 --> 01:15:28,991
between these two long-standing rivals.

1767
01:15:29,057 --> 01:15:31,793
Who took this round?

1768
01:15:31,860 --> 01:15:33,362
Who did Sung-tae choose?

1769
01:15:33,428 --> 01:15:34,763
Who will it be?

1770
01:15:34,830 --> 01:15:36,298
CHOI HYUN-SUK WINS

1771
01:15:36,365 --> 01:15:39,268
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S
HEO-TALIAN VONGOLE WINS

1772
01:15:39,835 --> 01:15:43,372
Choi Hyun-suk wins
and takes his fifth win in a row.

1773
01:15:43,438 --> 01:15:47,309
Hyun-suk's winning streak has not ended.

1774
01:15:48,076 --> 01:15:49,678
Are you not doing the apron thing?

1775
01:15:49,745 --> 01:15:51,446
No, not today.

1776
01:15:51,513 --> 01:15:53,382
WHY IS HE SO COMPOSED TODAY?

1777
01:15:53,448 --> 01:15:55,784
I must remain more humble
with more success.

1778
01:15:56,818 --> 01:16:00,289
-Stay humble with more success.
-He's writing it down.

1779
01:16:00,355 --> 01:16:02,391
Can you tell us the reason?

1780
01:16:02,457 --> 01:16:04,793
He took the lead in the order of tasting.

1781
01:16:04,860 --> 01:16:07,262
-It's the order.
-If it had changed,

1782
01:16:07,329 --> 01:16:10,832
-you wouldn't have tasted the latter.
-It might've been the case.

1783
01:16:10,899 --> 01:16:14,670
I also chose the one
with the kind of texture I liked.

1784
01:16:14,736 --> 01:16:18,874
-Although they were both good.
-Yes.

1785
01:16:18,941 --> 01:16:23,478
Chef Sohyi joined us today
as a special chef from Austria.

1786
01:16:23,545 --> 01:16:25,747
How was your day with us?

1787
01:16:25,814 --> 01:16:27,716
It was a new experience.

1788
01:16:27,783 --> 01:16:29,952
I also felt like I became younger,

1789
01:16:30,018 --> 01:16:32,254
competing with other young chefs here.

1790
01:16:32,321 --> 01:16:35,257
And it felt different once I got up there.

1791
01:16:35,324 --> 01:16:38,927
I want to apologize to people
whom I've eliminated.

1792
01:16:39,428 --> 01:16:40,829
IT WAS AN HONOR TO HAVE YOU

1793
01:16:40,896 --> 01:16:41,997
-I'm sorry.
-Yes.

1794
01:16:42,064 --> 01:16:44,633
Please put the star on Chef Hyun-suk!

1795
01:16:44,700 --> 01:16:46,602
This is his fifth win!

1796
01:16:49,137 --> 01:16:52,975
-He won all five rounds.
-Yes.

1797
01:16:53,609 --> 01:16:55,777
Please welcome today's fridge owners,

1798
01:16:55,844 --> 01:16:58,113
the hottest singles, Lee Da-hee and DEX!

1799
01:16:58,180 --> 01:16:59,848
There are ups and downs to staying single.

1800
01:16:59,915 --> 01:17:01,850
I personally think it's paradise.

1801
01:17:01,917 --> 01:17:03,719
I copied DEX's hairstyle.

1802
01:17:03,785 --> 01:17:05,520
Instead of DEX, I'm MEX.

1803
01:17:05,587 --> 01:17:06,722
AN HOMAGE TO DEX

1804
01:17:07,289 --> 01:17:10,626
LEARNING HOW TO FLIRT
FROM DATING EXPERTS

1805
01:17:11,259 --> 01:17:13,328
-Are you practicing?
-It's so difficult.

1806
01:17:15,464 --> 01:17:17,265
Mr. Show-off and Mr. Braise

1807
01:17:17,332 --> 01:17:19,835
-are up against each other!
-It may be a tough fight.

1808
01:17:19,901 --> 01:17:21,903
You're doing that today?

1809
01:17:21,970 --> 01:17:23,872
You're doing that?

1810
01:17:23,939 --> 01:17:26,074
-Chef Kang-rok became much faster.
-He has.

1811
01:17:26,141 --> 01:17:27,309
I'm usually this fast.

1812
01:17:27,376 --> 01:17:28,477
CHOI KANG-ROK HAS CHANGED!

1813
01:17:28,543 --> 01:17:29,544
He can even listen to us.

1814
01:17:29,611 --> 01:17:30,779
I'll make a Korean dish.

1815
01:17:30,846 --> 01:17:33,949
Is he measuring that with a ruler?

1816
01:17:34,016 --> 01:17:35,117
It looks so pretty.

1817
01:17:35,183 --> 01:17:36,885
I want to start this uproar.

1818
01:17:36,952 --> 01:17:40,155
-He's cutting lamb.
-Oh, no.

1819
01:17:40,222 --> 01:17:41,390
-Wait.
-It won't come out.

1820
01:17:41,456 --> 01:17:43,659
-It won't come out!
-No!

1821
01:17:44,593 --> 01:17:46,194
-Oh, no!
-This isn't working!

1822
01:17:50,232 --> 01:17:52,334
It must've been so good.

1823
01:18:02,511 --> 01:18:07,516
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
